30/03/2004
SKOPJE, Macedonia -- A teams of experts from the World Bank is in Macedonia to conduct the second comprehensive assessment of poverty levels in the country, <I>Utrinski Vesnik</I> reported Monday (29 March). According to the daily, a previous Bank survey found that two out of three citizens consider themselves poor. That figure contrasts with government statistics, which indicate that 30.2 per cent of people live below the poverty line. The results of the assessment are expected in three years.
In other news, the leader of the Democratic Party of Albanians, Arben Xhaferri, continued Monday to criticise Macedonia's ruling coalition, particularly the Democratic Union for Integration (DUI). Speaking in advance of the 14 April presidential election, Xhaferri said the DUI has failed to protect the interests of the Albanian minority. (Utrinski Vesnik - 30/03/04; Makfax - 29/03/04)
